11.25am Innings break Marsh walks off to warm applause holding the ball aloft for his first Test five wicket haul. What a superb performance from a much maligned player. England are all out six runs shy of 300. Hard to know what kind of score that is. It looks well under par but we shall see. One suspects if Smith gets started it will be. Buttler played beautifully to extend the innings with Leach's support but England failed to capitalise on a great platform. It's over to Stuart Broad and Jofra Archer to try and continue to torment David Warner and Marcus Harris.

Rahman: "So let me get this right.. Pat Cummins who bowled his heart out through out the series didn't have the luck to get a five wicket haul.. Marsh comes in as a cover and gets 5? Cruel!!"

Richard Demarch: "Biggest question now is whether Smith can get more runs than England."

William Rajan: "The highest number of Englishmen in double figures I've seen in a while... every cloud "

10.47am Right, time to hand the commentary over to Alex Malcolm, who is gagging to get stuck into England's tail.

10.44am Mike O: "Morning, aside from a few overs on day 2 of the 4th test, by my reckoning, Australia have bowled c300 overs in the space of under week. That's tantamount to 3.5 days in the field, which is a hefty workload regardless of Hazelwood and Cummins being supremely fit. On the surface this looks to be Oz comfortably ahead, but I think England are well in this game..."

It is a fair point, which makes Paine's decision at the toss extra curious. I guess one last big effort to get over the line isn't a massive ask, but hard to think that Smith wouldn't have made better use of the conditions than England's batsmen.

10.27am Congratulations pouring in for the Denlys after their safe delivery overnight ... and auspiciously, Little Miss Stevetta shares a birthday (well, certainly by Australian time if not UK) with a certain unforgettable legend of the sport. Shane Warne is 50 today! Which means, incidentally, that is must be exactly a year since I attempted to flog him out of this very ground, The Oval. How time flies!

And it must also be 14 years to the day since Warne celebrating his 36th birthday by watching England's Ashes winner parading through Trafalgar Square ...

10.12am The main man of the first day, however, was Australia's put-upon allrounder, Mitchell Marsh, who found consistent swing all day and harnessed it to come very canny attacking lines to rip the heart out of England's batting. But, yeah, he still doesn't quite feel as though he's got the backing of his countrymen back home. Poor chap...

Marsh's performance was the revival of a rarely-sighted art from Australia. Genuine swing bowling, as Daniel Brettig reports.

10.06am Hello again, we're about an hour away from the resumption, and what can Jos Buttler and Jack Leach eke out of the remnants of England's innings? The new ball is just two overs old, remember, and Australia's quicks will be (slightly) refreshed after a night's sleep. Realistically, England need to get close to 300 to feel fully back in contention after their subsidence yesterday afternoon.

Enigmas's Fan: "Prediction, we be all out by 11:45 but will have scored 350 by then. Any takers?" That sounds eminently plausible if Buttler gets his Beast Mode activated again ... I think he rather enjoyed giving it some humpty yesterday after an arduous series.

But a penny for Joe Root's thoughts after a scratchy 57 that summed up the nearly-but-not-quiteness of his current form. He had a huge slice of luck - three huge slices of luck - but couldn't make them count... as Alan Gardner recounts.

9.08am Good morning all. A bright sunny day in prospect at The Oval, and some early cheer for one member of the England team...

"Joe Denly's wife, Stacy, had their second child - a baby girl last night," an ECB spokesman tells us. "No name as yet. He arrived in time for the delivery! Joe is due back at the ground later this morning."

As you were. Play to resume at 11am. Full build-up shortly.

6.39pm Mitch Marsh is talking to Sky Sports, and confirms his injury was just a touch of cramp. "I was like a kid at Christmas this morning, can be a long tour when you're not playing, my goal was to run drinks as hard as I can." What a team player.

Anyway, that'll do for tonight, thanks for your comments, from myself, Andrew Miller, Alex Malcolm and Thilak Rama, good night!

6.32pm Well... what on earth to make of all that then? England were sent in, yet batted through the day, which has to count as an achievement. But after the start they got from the top five, their eventual 271 for 8 is a disappointment. But Buttler has found a familiar ally in Leach, and while he endures, this innings isn't over yet.

Excellent bowling from Australia's seamers, with the notable exception of Peter Siddle, who was poor. But Mitch Marsh exceeded expectations with a swing-laden four-for, and had it not been for a spate of dropped catches, Pat Cummins would have got the rewards his efforts deserved. And until Buttler starting lining up his length, Hazlewood was excellent too. Only four overs for Lyon though. Hurty-finger-itis?

Nabeel: "Lyon has hurty finger, Siddle hasn't found his rhythm, Hazlewood has bowled well but is being smoked all around, Marsh's having cramp issues, so the burden is all on Cummins again who should rather have been rested today" There is that too. Australia looked tired by the close. It all underlines the sense of missed opportunity for England's batsmen. Far too loose too often
